Let’s have all the compute syllables functions on had! I used all the header functions I learned from Chapter S to create the ount_syllables function.

is_special_ending <- function(ending) {
  is_es <- all(ending == c("e", "s"))
  is_ed <- all(ending == c("e", "d"))
  is_e_not_le <- ending[2] == "e" & ending[1] != "l" 
  is_es | is_ed | is_e_not_le
}

rm_special_endings <- function(word_letters) { 
  word_tail <- tail(word_letters, n = 2)
  if (is_special_ending(word_tail)) {
    if (word_tail[2] == "e") { word_letters[-length(word_letters)]
    } else {
    head(word_letters, n = -2)
    }
  } else {
    word_letters
  }
}

is_vowel <- function(letter) {
  letter %in% c("a", "e", "i", "o", "u", "y")
}

count_syllables <- function(word) {
  word_letters <- unlist(strsplit(word, split = "")) 
  if (length(word_letters) <= 3) {
      1
  } else {
      word_letters <- rm_special_endings(word_letters) 
      word_vowels <- is_vowel(word_letters) 
      sum(word_vowels) - sum(diff(which(word_vowels)) == 1)
  } 
}
keep_words <- function(words) { 
  words[nchar(words) > 0]
}

Now I will compute the Flesch reading ease score for each episode and assign it to the object RE. I conduct this computation by going through the chuncks of lines coresponding to each episode from episode 1 to episode 20. I utilize all the examples used in the Chapter S example. I calculate the ASL and ASW and then calcualte the RE score for each episode.

The words object is a list of all the words organzied by the sentence it is in. So let’s use the count_syllables function and apply it to every list within the words list object. Using the sapply function to go through each element in the list of lists, we get the number of syllables in each component. Then we can simply use the sum function to get the total number of syllables in the script. Then we can solve for ASW. This is our reading ease function.

reading_ease <- function(read){
  read <- paste(read, collapse = " ")
  sentences <- strsplit(read, split = "[.!?:;]")[[1]]
  sentences <- tolower(sentences)
  sentences <- gsub(pattern = "[[:punct:]]", replacement = "", sentences)
  words <- strsplit(sentences, split = " ")
  words <- lapply(words, keep_words)
  ASL <- sum(unlist(lapply(words, length))) / length(sentences)
  ASW <- sum(unlist(lapply(unlist(words), count_syllables))) / sum(unlist(lapply(words, length)))
  
  206.835 - (1.015 * ASL) - (84.6 * ASW)
}

Now lets call the reading ease function to calculate the RE score per episode using the for loop. So in the end the RE vector is the 122 REs for each episode. I used the head function to check that the data stored correctly and it did.

main_characters <- c("Andy Dwyer", "Ann Perkins", "April Ludgate", "Ben Wyatt", "Chris Traeger", "Donna Meagle", "Jerry Gergich", "Leslie Knope", "Ron Swanson", "Tom Haverford")

character_data <- data.frame("season" = NULL, "No.overall"=NULL, "episode" = NULL, "title" = NULL, "writer" = NULL, "character" = NULL, "reading_ease" = NULL)

for(i in seq_len(122)){
  episode_script <- scripts[which(scripts$Episode.Num == i),]
  info <- data.frame("season" = episode_data[i, 1],"No.overall"= episode_data[i, 2], "episode" = episode_data[i, 3], "title" = episode_data[i, 4], "writer" = episode_data[i, 6])
  for(j in main_characters){
    if (any(episode_script$Character == j)){
      character_script <- episode_script[which(episode_script$Character == j), ]
      re <- reading_ease(character_script[,2])
      newrow <- cbind(info, "character" = j, "reading_ease" = re)
      character_data <- rbind(character_data, newrow)
    }
  }
}

(b) Scatter Plots

Using the last example in the ?layout help file, we made a scatter_hist function which inputs two numeric vectors x and y of the same length and produces a scatterplot with marginal hists.

scatter_hist <- function(x, y, x_title = "", y_title = "", p_main = ""){
  
  xhist <- hist(x, plot = FALSE)
  yhist <- hist(y, plot = FALSE)
  top <- max(c(xhist$counts, yhist$counts))

  nf <- layout(matrix(c(2,0,1,3),2,2,byrow = TRUE), c(3,1), c(1,3), TRUE)
  par(mar = c(3,3,1,1))
  plot(x, y, xlab = x_title, ylab = y_title)
  par(mar = c(0,3,1,1))
  barplot(xhist$counts, axes = FALSE, ylim = c(0, top), space = 0,main=x_title)
  par(mar = c(3,0,1,1))
  barplot(yhist$counts, axes = FALSE, xlim = c(0, top), space = 0, horiz = TRUE,main=y_title)
}

Then using the scatter_hist function we made earlier, we created to plots that visualize firstly, ratings against the number of votes by episode and secondly, the viewers in millions against the ratings per episode.

Part III: Statistical Inference

Question 8: Make and Interpret Confidence Intervals

Here we use the reading score for Leslie by line from Q7. I set the seed to my UID using the set.seed function. Then I used the sample function to select a random sample of the 100 lines for leslie. Then, I used the t.test function to conduct a t test on the sample with a confidence intercal of 95%.

set.seed(904974926)

sample1 <- sample(leslie_RE, size = 100)
t.test(sample1,conf.level = 0.95)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  sample1
## t = 32.167, df = 99, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  87.00514 98.44456
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  92.72485

The mean of the sample is 92.72 and the 95% percent interval is bounded by 87.01 and 98.44. The true mean value is captured by the interval. This means we can say with 95% confidence that the mean of the sample is the mean of the data.

Now we are going to repeat these steps 1000 times, and find the proportion of confidence intervals that contain leslie’s true mean re score.

n <- 100
M <- 1000

confidence <- NULL
mean_leslie <- NULL

set.seed(904974926)

for (i in seq_len(M)){
  current_sample <- sample(leslie_RE, size = n)
  t_test <- t.test(current_sample, conf.level = 0.95)
  
  confidence <- rbind(confidence, t_test$conf.int)
  mean_leslie <- c(mean_leslie, mean(current_sample))
}

true_mean <- mean(leslie_RE) # Mean of the population of students 
true_mean
## [1] 89.97381
mean(confidence[,1] <= true_mean & confidence[,2] >= true_mean)
## [1] 0.941

Since we find that leslie’s true mean re score is 89.97, we can then say that the proportion of confidence intervals that contain her true mean re score is 0.941 which makes sense because it is almost 95%.

Question 9: State and Test a Hypothesis

We are interested in using the mean US views per million per month data to decide if the numerical variable, mean views of a particular month, and the numerical variable, number of episodes per month, are are dependent variables. Basically, we are trying to figure out if there is some sort of corelation between the month certain episodes comes out and the number of viewers in that particular month. To test our hypothesis, since we are comparing two numerical variables, we are going to plot a regression line using the lm and abline functions.

month_views <- list()

for(i in 1:12){
  index <- grep(pattern = month.name[i], episode_data$`Original air date`)
  month_views[[i]] <- episode_data$`U.S. viewers(millions)`[index]
}

names(month_views) <- month.name

#then calculate averages 
episode_num <- unlist(lapply(month_views,length)) # number of episodes per month  
view_avg <- unlist(lapply(month_views,mean)) # average views per month 

plot(episode_num, view_avg, col=rainbow(12), pch = 19, xlab="Number of Episodes",ylab="viewers per million")
legend("bottomleft", month.name, col= rainbow(12), pch = 19)
lin_reg <- lm(view_avg~episode_num)
abline(lin_reg[[1]])

From this we can see that the more episodes that there are a month, the less viewers there are. This means that there is a linear relationship between these two numerical variables, number of episodes per month and number of views per month. After some research, we believe that we get this strange negative linear relationship because of this: The months with the fewest episodes and the highest rates, like September and December, occur since these are the beginning of the season and where the season takes a break after the holdiays. While these are the months which fewest episodes (since the season starts later in september and it breaks for the holidays later in december), they are the most watched. The other months with higher number of episodes, such as November and Februrary, have fewer viewers per million since these months represent lulls in the show where maybe not as exciting things are happening and these are just fun, filler episodes. While we do not have enough data to claim that we are 100% sure on our hypothesis, based on this explanation, we can say this is why we believe there is a correlation between months and number of views.
